Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

The main issue to be addressed is identifying the reason for the decline in new monthly subscribers compared to the previous year. It is believed that the current webpage design may be the cause.

To accomplish our goals, we have the following objectives:

Investigate if users spend more time on the new landing page compared to the existing landing page. Determine whether the conversion rate of the new page is higher than that of the old page. Examine the relationship between the preferred language of the users and their converted status. Determine if there is any variation in the time spent on the new page for users of different preferred languages.

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

plt.show()

print("Total & average time spent on the existing landing page across 50 users (control group): ", 
      str(round(abtest_old["time_spent_on_the_page"].sum(), 2)) + " mins and", 
      str(round(abtest_old["time_spent_on_the_page"].mean(), 2)) + " mins.")

print("Total & average time spent on the new landing page across 50 users (treatment group): ", 
      str(round(abtest_new["time_spent_on_the_page"].sum(), 2)) + " mins and", 
      str(round(abtest_new["time_spent_on_the_page"].mean(), 2)) + " mins.")

Total & average time spent on the existing landing page across 50 users (control group):  226.62 mins and 4.53 mins.
Total & average time spent on the new landing page across 50 users (treatment group):  311.16 mins and 6.22 mins.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

The null and alternative hypothesis can be formulated as:

$H_0$ : The mean time spent on the new landing page is the same as the mean time spent on the old landing page

$H_1$ : The mean time spent on the new landing page is higher than the mean time spent on the old landing page

Let new landing page and exist'ing page be $\mu_1, \mu_2$ respectively. Mathematically, the above formulated hypothesis can be written as:

$H_0:\mu_1 = \mu_2$

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_1:\mu_1>\mu_2$

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Based on the above information, we select a Two Sample Independent T-test for Equality of Means with Unequal Standard Deviation

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

As given in the problem statement, we select $\alpha$ = 0.5

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [27]:
μ_1, μ_2 = abtest_new["time_spent_on_the_page"].mean() , abtest_old["time_spent_on_the_page"].mean()
std1, std2 = abtest_new["time_spent_on_the_page"].std() , abtest_old["time_spent_on_the_page"].std()
print("μ_1, μ_2, std1, std2:", str(round(μ_1,2))+",", str(round(μ_2,2))+",", str(round(std1,2))+","\
      , str(round(std2,2))+".")

μ_1, μ_2, std1, std2: 6.22, 4.53, 1.82, 2.58.

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [28]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

#finding the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(abtest_new["time_spent_on_the_page"], abtest_old["time_spent_on_the_page"], \
                               equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [29]:
print('The p-value is ', p_value, 'and the significance level alpha is 0.05')

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549 and the significance level alpha is 0.05

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Since the p-value (0.00014) is less than the significance level, we can reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we do have enough evidence to support the claim that the mean time spent on the new landing page is higher tha mean time spent on the old landing page

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

% converted - old landing page:  42.0%
% converted - new landing page:  66.0%

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

The null and alternative hypothesis can be formulated as:

$H_0$ : The conversion rate for the new landing page is the same as the conversion rate for the existing page

$H_1$ : The conversion rate for the new landing page is greater than the conversion rate for the existing page

Let new landing page and existing page be c_1, c_2 respectively. Mathematically, the above formulated hypothesis can be written as:

H0 : c_1 = c_2

Ha : c_1 > c_2

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

To test the proportions, a Two Proportion Z-test is selected.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

The significance level set is at 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [39]:

4. Is the time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

Perform visual analysis¶

In [2]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
sns.boxplot(x="language_preferred", y="time_spent_on_the_page",\
            data=abtest_new.sort_values("language_preferred", ascending = True));
plt.ylabel("time spent on the new landing page (mins)")
plt.show()

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let μ_1, μ_2, μ_3 be the mean time spent on the new landing page for the different language users - English, French and Spanish respectively.

$\H_0$ : Null Hypothesis - The time spent on the new landing page is the same for all languages μ1 = μ2 = μ3

$\H_a $: At least one of μ1, μ2, μ3 is different from the rest

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

The analysis involves testing the means of multiple groups, and therefore, we selected the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) test.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

The significance level set is at 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

The next step is to check the normality and equality of variance assumptions. To test for normality, we will use the Shapiro-Wilk test. For the equality of variance, we will use Levene's test.

Specifically, for the Shapiro-Wilk test:

$\H_0$: Time spent on the new landing page follows a normal distribution

$\H_a$: Time spent on the new landing page does not follow a normal distribution

In [2]:
# finding the p-value
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(abtest_new['time_spent_on_the_page']) 
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.8040016293525696

As the p-value is greater than the significance level, we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that the time spent on the new landing page follows a normal distribution.

Levene's Test¶

In [ ]:
H0:Null Hypothesis - All population variances (time spent on new landing page for different preferred languages) are equal.
Ha:Alternate Hypothesis - Atleast one variance is different from the rest.
In [1]:
from scipy.stats import levene
statistic, p_value = levene( abtest_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest_new['language_preferred']=="English"], 
                             abtest_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest_new['language_preferred']=="French"], 
                             abtest_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest_new['language_preferred']=="Spanish"])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.46711357711340173

Since the p-value is greater than the significance level, we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that all population variances are equal.

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [2]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# perform one-way anova test
test_stat, p_value = f_oneway(abtest_new.loc[abtest_new['language_preferred'] == 'English', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              abtest_new.loc[abtest_new['language_preferred'] == 'French', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              abtest_new.loc[abtest_new['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish', 'time_spent_on_the_page'])
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.43204138694325955

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [3]:
print('The p-value is ', p_value, 'and the significance level alpha is 0.05')

The p-value is  0.43204138694325955 and the significance level alpha is 0.05

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Since the p-value is much larger than the significance level, we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, we cannot conclude that at least one mean time spent on the new landing page for the three preferred languages is different.

However, we did not find enough statistical evidence to conclude that the conversion rate is dependent on the preferred language using a chi-square test for independence.

Additionally, we did not find enough evidence to support the claim that at least one mean time spent on the new landing page for different preferred languages is different from the rest at the preset 5% significance level.

An ANOVA test was used for this, and normality and equality of variances were verified.

Based on the statistical analysis, it can be concluded that the new landing page is superior to the old landing page in terms of both time spent by users and conversion rate. Therefore, it is recommended that the new landing page be fully adopted

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

The conversion rate for the new landing page is higher at 66% compared to 42% for the old landing page.

The dataset contains roughly an equal number of users preferring English, French, and Spanish.

The conversion rate changes for the new landing page compared to the old landing page are -105, 75%, and 36.4% for English, French, and Spanish, respectively.

We have obtained statistical evidence to support the claim that the mean time spent on the new landing page is higher than the mean time spent on the old landing page, using a two independent sample T-test for equality of means (Unequal std dev.). Similarly, we found enough evidence to support the claim that the conversion rate for the new landing page is higher than the conversion rate for the old landing page using a two proportion Z-test.

Although the dataset did not provide enough statistical evidence to support the claim that the conversion rate is dependent on the preferred language, exploratory data analysis revealed that French and Spanish users had a higher conversion rate on the new landing page, while English users had a slightly lower conversion rate.

This observation may require further investigation to understand the underlying reasons and take appropriate action.
